Filtering dataset

There are a number of reasons remove rows because of missing data: (Referenced from propublica/compas-analysis on github)

##If the charge date of a defendants Compas scored crime was not within 30 days from when the person was arrested, we assume that because of data quality reasons, that we do not have the right offense. ## Coded the recidivist flag is_recid to be -1 if we could not find a compas case at all. ##In a similar vein, ordinary traffic offenses those with a c_charge_degree of O will not result in Jail time are removed (only two of them). ## Filtered the underlying data from Broward county to include only those rows representing people who had either recidivated in two years, or had at least two years outside of a correctional facility.

df <- dplyr::select(raw_data, age, c_charge_degree, race, age_cat, score_text, sex, priors_count, days_b_screening_arrest, decile_score, is_recid, two_year_recid, c_jail_in, c_jail_out) %>% 
        filter(days_b_screening_arrest <= 30) %>%
        filter(days_b_screening_arrest >= -30) %>%
        filter(is_recid != -1) %>%
        filter(c_charge_degree != "O") %>%
        filter(score_text != 'N/A')
nrow(df)

The previous bar graph shows the distribution of people in High, Medium and Low Risk crimes, with most of the people being categorised in the low risk crimes.

The following correlation plot shows correlation between different variables. This is helpful so as to shortlist predictors that we would want to use for our models subsequently.

library(corrplot)
## corrplot 0.84 loaded
# correlations
nums <- unlist(lapply(raw_data, is.numeric))
df <- raw_data[ , nums]
df[is.na(df)] <- -1        ###### Replaced NAs in dataset with -1 indicating missing value #
correlations<- cor(df)
corrplot(correlations,method = "number")  #blue indicates positive correlation, red indicates negative

As we can see, there is strong positive correlation between is_recid and two_year_recid indicating that if a person commits a crime for the first time, they are likely to commit a crime for another year too.

Box-plot for Race vs Decile Score

cbPalette <- c("#999999", "#E69F00", "#56B4E9", "#009E73", "#F0E442", "#0072B2", "#D55E00", "#CC79A7")

options(scipen = 4)

qplot(data = raw_data, x = race, y = decile_score, fill = I(cbPalette[3]), geom = "boxplot",main = "Decile Score vs Race")

As we observe from the plot, African-American and native americans have higher decile scores as compared to other ethnicities. This indicates a potential bias in the scoring pattern.

Variation of Decile Score with Age

ggplot(data = raw_data, aes(x = age_cat, y = decile_score,color=as.factor(age_cat))) + 
  geom_jitter() +
  stat_smooth(method = "lm", col = "red")+guides(color=FALSE)+xlab("Age")+ylab("Decile Score")

There is higher density of population between the age group 25-45 that has a higher decile score as compared to the other age groups.

Correlation Plot for 2 years violent data

library(corrplot)
# correlations
nums1 <- unlist(lapply(raw_data_violent, is.numeric))
df_corr <- raw_data_violent[ , nums1]
df_corr[is.na(df_corr)] <- -1        ###### Replaced NAs in dataset with -1 indicating missing value #
correlations_v<- cor(df_corr)
corrplot(correlations_v,method = "number")  #blue indicates positive correlation, red indicates negative

High positive correlation again observed between 1 year and 2 year recidivism rates indicating that if an individual is convicted of a violent crime in the first year, they are likely to reoffend. Violent decile score also positively correlated with the decile score for this reason.

###Introduction and Goal Setting

In this criminal recidivism project we aim to come up with a model to aid and assist judges in making decisions to decide how likely a criminal is to commit a crime again. Our goal in this project is to come up with a model which has a high specificity that is a good true negative rate.

Specificity aka True Negative Rate (TNR)=#observations correctly classified as non-events/#observations that did not have the event =T N/(T N + F P) A classifier with high Specificity is desirable here because in our opinion, False Positives (extending the conviction for a person who is not likely to commit a crime) are more costly than False Negatives (releasing a person who is likely to commit a crime again). We have taken in cosideration the specificity-sensitivity trade off.

##Feature Selection

The original compas file had 53 variables.However, in order to proceed with the analysis we decided to drop some variables. We explored the data on the CSV file and decided which variables to use. We started out by eliminating the obvious variables. For example, id, name, dob variables we realised would have no bearing on the outcome of the recidivism prediction.We then removed the other identity providing variables like v_case_number, r_case_number, vr_case_number. We then removed the date variables as they too would not be useful in predicting recidivism. This resulted in us eliminating 19 variables. After that, we used our correlation plots. There was a obviously high correlation between age and age-category and it made more sense to use age category as we could then make age a categorical variable. We then removed the decile score values and other compas parameters as they were the output of compas, and if we were to make a model alternative to Compas, using Compass output would make little sense. We now had removed 27 variables. Upon running a Random Forest model , we realised that we could not use the r_charge_degree and r_charge_desc as there was a very high number of missing values in the data. We this eliminated all the charge degrees and their description. We eliminated the violent_recidivism parameters as well as we are making a separate model to predict violent recidivism. This left us with 12 variables to work with.

We started out my making a custom built function which we would use through our project to give us the confusion matrix and performance metrics of the different models that we fit for different data. The parameters that we pass to this model are the results from our model, the actual predicted values, the cutoff values and the type of parameters that we need for the function to evaluate.

classMetrics <- function(score, y, cutoff, 
                         type = c("all", "accuracy", "sensitivity", 
                                  "specificity", "ppv", "npv", "precision", 
                                  "recall")) {

# This command throws an error if the user specifies a "type" that
# isn't supported by this function
type <- match.arg(type, several.ok = TRUE)  
our_result<-numeric()
for(i in 1:length(score)){
  if(score[i]>cutoff){
    our_result<-c(our_result,1) #if greater then cutoff 1
  }
  else{
    our_result<-c(our_result,0) #if lesser than or equal to cutoff then 0
  }
}
#We shall now create the confusion matrix
y.fakefactor<-factor(y) #Converting y into factors
or.factor<-factor(our_result) #Converting our_result into factors
x=table(round(our_result), y)
names(dimnames(x)) <- c("predicted", "actual")

ym<-as.matrix(x)
new_mat <- matrix(0,nrow=2,ncol=2)  
# 'new_mat' rows getting filled with `mat` values
if(nrow(ym)==1){
new_mat[1,] <- ym

ym=new_mat
}
sum(ym)
 # print("y[2,1]")
 # print(ym[2,1])
acc<-(ym[2,2]+ym[1,1])/sum(ym)
sensi<-ym[2,2]/(ym[2,2]+ym[1,2])
spec<-ym[1,1]/(ym[1,1]+ym[2,1])
ppv<-ym[2,2]/(ym[2,2]+ym[2,1])
npv<- ym[1,1]/(ym[1,1]+ym[1,2])
prec<-ym[2,2]/(ym[2,2]+ym[2,1])
recall<-ym[2,2]/(ym[2,2]+ym[1,2])

perfv<-c(acc,sensi,spec,ppv,npv,prec,recall)
perfdf<-data.frame(perfv) #Convert the vector into a dataframe
rownames(perfdf) <- c("accuracy", "sensitivity", 
                                  "specificity", "ppv", "npv", "precision", 
                                  "recall")

perf=data.frame()

names(perfdf) <- "values"
library(pracma)
if(strcmp(type[1],"all")) {
ret_list<-  list(conf.mat = as.matrix(x), perf = perfdf)
}else{

ret_list<-list(conf.mat = as.matrix(x), perf = subset(perfdf, subset=rownames(perfdf) %in% type))
}

return(ret_list)
}

###2. Decision Tree Model - Full and Pruned We then fit a decision tree model based on all the variables(full decision tree). A decision tree reduces ambiguity in decision-making.One big advantage of the decision tree model is its transparent nature. We used decision tree analysis as it has an advantage in its ability to assign specific values to problem, decisions, and outcomes of each decision. Unlike other decision-making models, the decision tree makes explicit all possible alternatives and traces each alternative to its conclusion in a single view, allowing for easy comparison among the various alternatives. The use of separate nodes to denote user defined decisions, uncertainties, and end of process lends further clarity and transparency to the decision-making process.After fitting, we observed the CP table for the full decision tree. We then used the 1SE rule to determine the best CP value. We then pruned our tree. After pruning it, we used the ClassMetrics function to understand the performance of the pruned decision tree. This decision tree had a moderately high value(~55%) of specificity, which is not as good as our random forest model. It did have a higher value for sensitivity ast 77%.

Reference: https://www.brighthubpm.com/project-planning/106000-advantages-of-decision-tree-analysis/

###3. Logistic Regression Model Thirdly, we fit a logistic regression model based on all the variables. Logistic Regression measures the relationship between the dependent variable (our label, what we want to predict) and the one or more independent variables (our features), by estimating probabilities using its underlying logistic function.These probabilities must then be transformed into binary values in order to actually make a prediction. This is the task of the logistic function, also called the sigmoid function. The Sigmoid-Function is an S-shaped curve that can take any real-valued number and map it into a value between the range of 0 and 1, but never exactly at those limits. This values between 0 and 1 will then be transformed into either 0 or 1 using a threshold classifier. Uponbuilding a logistic regression model, we measured the performabce of our model. Our model does well in terms of the trade off between specificity and sensitivity. We have a good sensitivity rate(77%) while maintaining a decent specificity rate(~55%).

Reference: https://machinelearning-blog.com/2018/04/23/logistic-regression-101/

classMetrics <- function(score, y, cutoff, 
                         type = c("all", "accuracy", "sensitivity", 
                                  "specificity", "ppv", "npv", "precision", 
                                  "recall")) {

# This command throws an error if the user specifies a "type" that
# isn't supported by this function
type <- match.arg(type, several.ok = TRUE)  
our_result<-numeric()
for(i in 1:length(score)){
  if(score[i]>cutoff){
    our_result<-c(our_result,1) #if greater then cutoff 1
  }
  else{
    our_result<-c(our_result,0) #if lesser than or equal to cutoff then 0
  }
}
#We shall now create the confusion matrix
y.fakefactor<-factor(y) #Converting y into factors
or.factor<-factor(our_result) #Converting our_result into factors
x=table(round(our_result), y)
names(dimnames(x)) <- c("predicted", "actual")

ym<-as.matrix(x)
new_mat <- matrix(0,nrow=2,ncol=2)  
# 'new_mat' rows getting filled with `mat` values
if(nrow(ym)==1){
new_mat[1,] <- ym

ym=new_mat
}
sum(ym)
acc<-(ym[2,2]+ym[1,1])/sum(ym)
sensi<-ym[2,2]/(ym[2,2]+ym[1,2])
spec<-ym[1,1]/(ym[1,1]+ym[2,1])
ppv<-ym[2,2]/(ym[2,2]+ym[2,1])
npv<- ym[1,1]/(ym[1,1]+ym[1,2])
prec<-ym[2,2]/(ym[2,2]+ym[2,1])
recall<-ym[2,2]/(ym[2,2]+ym[1,2])

perfv<-c(acc,sensi,spec,ppv,npv,prec,recall)
perfdf<-data.frame(perfv) #Convert the vector into a dataframe
rownames(perfdf) <- c("accuracy", "sensitivity", 
                                  "specificity", "ppv", "npv", "precision", 
                                  "recall")

perf=data.frame()

names(perfdf) <- "values"
library(pracma)
if(strcmp(type[1],"all")) {
ret_list<-  list(conf.mat = as.matrix(x), perf = perfdf)
}else{

ret_list<-list(conf.mat = as.matrix(x), perf = subset(perfdf, subset=rownames(perfdf) %in% type))
}

return(ret_list)
}

##Comparison with the compass model Compass model provides a specificity of 77% and sensitivity of 75%. But the cost of convicting a person who is less likely to commit a crime is much higher. 

###### COMPAS MODEL ######
library(knitr)
sizeraw = nrow(df2)
sample = sample.int(2, size=sizeraw, prob=c(.7,.3), replace=TRUE)
trainsample=(sample==1)     # put 70% of the observations in the training sample
predsample=(sample==2)


df_cmps <- mutate(df2, crime_factor = factor(c_charge_degree)) %>%
      mutate(age_factor = as.factor(age_cat)) %>%
      within(age_factor <- relevel(age_factor, ref = 1)) %>%
      mutate(race_factor = factor(race)) %>%
      within(race_factor <- relevel(race_factor, ref = 3)) %>%
      mutate(gender_factor = factor(sex, labels= c("Female","Male"))) %>%
      within(gender_factor <- relevel(gender_factor, ref = 2)) %>%
      mutate(score_factor = factor(score_text != "Low", labels = c("LowScore","HighScore")))
model <- glm(score_factor ~ gender_factor + age_factor + race_factor +
                            priors_count + crime_factor + two_year_recid, family="binomial", data=df_cmps[trainsample,])
summary(model)

Conclusion: For both our datasets recidivism and violent recidivism, we have used random forest as our best models

The above ROC plot compares the criminal recidivism models that we fit with the COMPAS model. In order predicitng recidivism, the compas predictor outperformed our best model -> the random forest model. We conclude this based on the ROC Curves of the three models that we fit. Howvever, we will not limit ourseleves only to the ROC curve. We shall use the performance metric as well to make our decision. As stated in the beginning our aim is to make a model with high specificity while maintaining a decent tradeoff with sensitivity. Our RF model has 81% specificity which is very high compared to the compas model.The other models logistic regression and decision tree do not have a good trade off between sensitivity and specificity.
